items.title: Hymenoptera spp., Tettigoniidae spp.
items.content_text: I saw this wasp fly from a tree carrying the katydid. It landed near a hole in the ground and dropped the katydid. The wasp then went into the hold and did a bit of excavating and then dragged the katydid into the hole.

items.title: Xanthopimpla spp.
items.content_text: There were two of these small wasps, both were very interested in whatever was curled up inside a cluster of leaves.

items.title: Theronia steindachneri
items.content_text: I think this is Theronia steindachneri reference: https://sites.google.com/site/insectsoftasmaniahymenoptera2/suborder-apocrita--terebrant/ichneumonidae-ichneuman-wasps/genus-theronia/theronia-steindachneri There were two of these that were very interested in the same dead, curled leaf, which I assume contained what they wanted to lay their eggs on or in.

items.title: Sceliphron laetum
items.content_text: Large-ish wasp collecting mud for a nest. About five seen around the edges of the dam. Quite timid and tricky to photograph! After a bit of a search I've attempted an ID with Sceliphron laetum based on the facial features seen on the photo and this information here: http://museum.wa.gov.au/research/collections/terrestrial-zoology/entomology-insect-collection/entomology-factsheets/sceliphron

items.title: Lophyrotoma spp.
items.content_text: 8 photos included. At least 100 seen this afternoon all around Woodlands Historic Park. I think this is Lophyrotoma interrupta, which seems to vary considerably from what little information that I can find online e.g. http://www.bowerbird.org.au/observations/2770
